# SESSION PROTOCOL

---

## ENTER SESSION CHECKLIST

Run this at the start of every new conversation before doing any work.

1. **Check the time**
   Run: `powershell -Command "Get-Date -Format 'dddd, MMMM dd yyyy h:mm tt'"`
   Report the time to Ryan and state peak vs. off-peak status.

2. **Pull latest from GitHub**
   Run: `cd "c:\App Development\sticker-quest"; git pull origin main`
   If there are conflicts or errors, report them to Ryan before proceeding.
   If already up to date, note it briefly and move on.

3. **Read PROJECT_CONTEXT.md**
   Confirm current phase, open flags, and any decisions that affect today's work.

4. **Read the last 2 entries in PATCH_NOTES.md**
   Know what was done in the last session and what was left unfinished.

5. **Surface the top open Known Flag**
   Check the "Known Flags" section of PROJECT_CONTEXT.md. Name the single most
   urgent unresolved issue so Ryan stays aware of it — even if we're not fixing it today.

6. **Check .env has real values (if code work is planned)**
   If the session involves Supabase features, verify EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL and
   EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY in .env are not placeholder strings.
   If blank: warn Ryan that Star Mail and any backend features will silently fail.

7. **Give Ryan a 3-line briefing:**
   - "Current phase: [X]. Last session: [what was done]."
   - "Open items: [top 1-2 things that need to happen next]."
   - "Time status: [peak/off-peak and what that means today]."

8. **Ask what Ryan wants to work on** — do not assume and charge ahead.

---

## EXIT SESSION CHECKLIST

Run this before ending any conversation where meaningful work was done.

1. **Update PATCH_NOTES.md**
   Log what was accomplished, any decisions made, and any new open items.

2. **Update PROJECT_CONTEXT.md**
   If any decisions changed the project direction, phase status, or known flags — update it.

3. **Run linter before committing**
   Run: `cd "c:\App Development\sticker-quest"; npx expo lint`
   If errors appear, fix them before committing. Never push broken code to GitHub.
   If warnings only (no errors), note them but proceed.

4. **Flag new npm packages if any were installed**
   If any `npm install` commands were run this session, tell Ryan:
   "New packages were added. If you open this project on another device,
   run: npm install — in the terminal first."

5. **Commit and push to GitHub**
   Run git status to confirm what changed, then:
   - `cd "c:\App Development\sticker-quest"; git add .`
   - Commit with a clear plain-English summary message
   - `git push origin main`
   Tell Ryan: "Everything is saved to GitHub. Your work is backed up."
   If push fails, explain the problem plainly and give a simple fix.

6. **Next session options — prioritized**
   Do not just say "Your next move." Instead, give Ryan a short prioritized menu
   of 2–4 options based on:
   - Current phase and what's blocking progress
   - Whether a time-sensitive promo (Claude 2x, etc.) is active or expiring soon
   - Whether we're currently in peak or off-peak hours
   - What's sitting in PENDING_SPRINTS.md
   - Any open critical flags in PROJECT_CONTEXT.md

   Format it like this:

   **Next Session — Your Options (in my recommended order):**
   1. [URGENT if applicable] [Option name] — [1-sentence reason why] | ⏱ ~X min (reliable/may vary)
   2. [Option name] — [1-sentence reason why] | ⏱ ~X min (reliable/may vary)
   3. [Option name] — [1-sentence reason why] | ⏱ ~X min (reliable/may vary)
   *(Optional) Off-peak bonus: [Name of Claude Pro sprint to run] — best time: [when]*

   Time estimate rules:
   - Content tasks (Claude Pro sprints, JSON merges): label as "reliable" — these are predictable
   - Code tasks (building features, fixing bugs): label as "may vary" — unexpected issues are normal
   - Never give a code estimate without a "may vary" warning
   - If a code task has a known hidden risk (e.g., touching a stub that may cascade), flag it explicitly

   Always give a recommended order. Never just list options without a preference.
   Always factor in deadlines and promo windows when ranking.

7. **Flag anything time-sensitive**
   If something needs to happen before a deadline (e.g., March 27 Claude Pro sprint),
   say so explicitly at the end of the session.

